---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import rates from '../data/rates.json';
import sector from '../data/sector.json';

const R25 = rates.years['2025-26'];
const R26 = rates.years['2026-27'];
const H = rates.company_headlines_26_27;
const prev = rates.previous_year_context;

const pct = (a, b) => (((b - a) / a) * 100).toFixed(1);
const fmt = (n, d = 2) => '£' + n.toFixed(d);
const sign = (n) => (parseFloat(n) > 0 ? '+' : '') + n + '%';

const rows = [
  { label: 'Water supply, per cubic metre', a: R25.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp, b: R26.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp, dp: 3 },
  { label: 'Water supply, annual standing charge', a: R25.water_supply_standing_gbp, b: R26.water_supply_standing_gbp, dp: 2 },
  { label: 'Wastewater, per cubic metre', a: R25.wastewater_per_cubic_metre_gbp, b: R26.wastewater_per_cubic_metre_gbp, dp: 3 },
  { label: 'Wastewater, annual standing charge', a: R25.wastewater_standing_gbp, b: R26.wastewater_standing_gbp, dp: 2 },
  { label: 'Surface water drainage, annual', a: R25.surface_water_drainage_gbp, b: R26.surface_water_drainage_gbp, dp: 2 }
];

const waterM3Delta = pct(R25.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp, R26.water_supply_per_cubic_metre_gbp);
const waterStandingDelta = pct(R25.water_supply_standing_gbp, R26.water_supply_standing_gbp);

const combinedCompoundPct = (((1 + prev.combined_average_rise_pct / 100) * (1 + H.combined_average_rise_pct / 100)) - 1) * 100;
const waterOnlyCompoundPct = (((1 + prev.combined_average_rise_pct / 100) * (1 + H.water_supply_only_rise_pct / 100)) - 1) * 100;
const compoundCombined = combinedCompoundPct.toFixed(1);
const compoundWaterOnly = waterOnlyCompoundPct.toFixed(1);
---

<Base title="Overview" currentPath="/" dek="The two-year compound rise on your Southern Water bill">
  <h1 class="hed">
    From April 2025 to April 2026, our water bills have risen by roughly {compoundCombined}%.
    <span class="small">Southern Water's current-year headline is eight per cent. What is going on?</span>
  </h1>

  <aside class="action-panel" aria-label="What you can do">
    <p class="action-panel-lede">
      <strong>Take action now.</strong>
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="btn primary" href="/complain">Draft a complaint to Southern Water</a>
      <a class="btn ghost" href="/write-to-mp">Write to your MP</a>
    </div>
    <p class="action-panel-note">
      If you are struggling to pay, Southern Water's social tariff gives at least a 45 per cent discount for eligible households.<a class="cite" href="/sources#12" aria-label="Source 12">12</a>
    </p>
  </aside>

  <h2>What's happened</h2>

  <p>
    In April 2025, the average combined household bill went up by {prev.combined_average_rise_pct} per cent<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a>. In April 2026, a further {H.combined_average_rise_pct} per cent was added on top<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a>. Rises compound. A bill that was £100 in March 2025 is about £{((1 + prev.combined_average_rise_pct/100) * (1 + H.combined_average_rise_pct/100) * 100).toFixed(0)} now.
  </p>

  <p>
    For households that only take water supply from Southern Water, the two-year compound is steeper still: {prev.combined_average_rise_pct} per cent followed by {H.water_supply_only_rise_pct} per cent, which is about {compoundWaterOnly} per cent over two years<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a>. Per cubic metre, the water-supply rate alone went up by {waterM3Delta} per cent this April<a class="cite" href="/sources#1" aria-label="Source 1">1</a>. The standing charge went up by {waterStandingDelta} per cent<a class="cite" href="/sources#1" aria-label="Source 1">1</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="callout">
    The 2025 rise was described at the time as front-loaded, to pay for investment.<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a> The 2026 rise is additional.
  </p>

  <h2>The new rates, set against last year</h2>

  <p>
    These are Southern Water's own published rates<a class="cite" href="/sources#1" aria-label="Source 1">1</a> for metered households, for the year from 1 April 2026 to 31 March 2027.
  </p>

  <table class="rates-table">
    <caption class="visually-hidden">Southern Water metered household rates, 2025-26 compared with 2026-27.</caption>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th scope="col">Charge</th>
        <th scope="col" class="num">2025-26</th>
        <th scope="col" class="num">2026-27</th>
        <th scope="col" class="num">Change</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {rows.map(r => {
        const d = pct(r.a, r.b);
        const up = parseFloat(d) > 0;
        return (
          <tr>
            <td>{r.label}</td>
            <td class="num">{fmt(r.a, r.dp)}</td>
            <td class="num">{fmt(r.b, r.dp)}</td>
            <td class={`num delta ${up ? '' : 'delta-down'}`}>{sign(d)}</td>
          </tr>
        );
      })}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Who approved the rise</h2>

  <p>
    Ofwat approved the increases as part of the PR24 Final Determination in December 2024, which sets price controls for every water company in England and Wales for 2025-2030<a class="cite" href="/sources#3" aria-label="Source 3">3</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Southern Water appealed, along with four other companies. They did not argue the determination was too high. They argued it was too low. The Competition and Markets Authority published its final redeterminations on 26 March 2026<a class="cite" href="/sources#4" aria-label="Source 4">4</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Household customers cannot appeal Ofwat's decision directly. Ofwat does not handle individual bill complaints. There is no retail market: you cannot switch supplier.
  </p>

  <h2>Where the money went</h2>

  <p>
    Ofwat's Monitoring Financial Resilience Report for 2022-23 records two equity injections into the Southern Water group from funds managed by Macquarie Asset Management. £1.1 billion was injected in September 2021, of which £530 million reached the regulated entity that actually supplies your water. A further £550 million was injected in October 2023, of which £375 million reached the regulated entity.<a class="cite" href="/sources#8" aria-label="Source 8">8</a>
  </p>

  <p>
    £1.65 billion went in at the top of the group. About £905 million reached the operating company. The difference, roughly £745 million, stayed at the parent level.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ofwat's own position, in the same report, is that "it is not sufficient for companies to justify their dividend payments on the basis of meeting holding company obligations, and without also considering performance of the regulatory company to support that dividend decision."<a class="cite" href="/sources#8" aria-label="Source 8">8</a> The regulator has since strengthened the dividend-policy licence condition.
  </p>

  <h2>Why 8 per cent and 28 per cent both appear</h2>

  <p>
    Southern Water says the average combined household bill for 2026-27 is going up by {H.combined_average_rise_pct} per cent<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a>. That is an average across three types of customer:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Combined water and wastewater: about {sign(H.combined_average_rise_pct)}, or {fmt(H.combined_average_monthly_rise_gbp)} a month<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a></li>
    <li>Water supply only: {sign(H.water_supply_only_rise_pct)}, or {fmt(H.water_supply_only_monthly_rise_gbp)} a month<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a></li>
    <li>Wastewater only: {sign(H.wastewater_only_rise_pct)}, a saving of about {fmt(H.wastewater_only_monthly_saving_gbp)} a month<a class="cite" href="/sources#2" aria-label="Source 2">2</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Whether the bill in front of you shows a rise of 8 per cent or nearer 28 per cent for this year alone depends on which services you get, how much water you use, and whether the billing period crosses 1 April. The two-year compound is a separate question from the averaging, and the compound is always higher than the headline.
  </p>

  <h2>On dividends at sector level</h2>

  <p>
    Southern Water states that it has paid no dividends to external shareholders since 2017<a class="cite" href="/sources#7" aria-label="Source 7">7</a>. That checks out. The dividend question is more visible at sector level.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ofwat's financial monitoring reports show total water-company borrowings of £{sector.sector.total_borrowing_31_march_2025_gbp_bn} billion at 31 March 2025<a class="cite" href="/sources#5" aria-label="Source 5">5</a>, up from net debt of £{sector.sector.net_debt_31_march_2024_gbp_bn} billion a year earlier<a class="cite" href="/sources#6" aria-label="Source 6">6</a>. The sector-wide dividend total for 2023-24 was about £{sector.sector.dividends_declared_2023_24_gbp_bn} billion<a class="cite" href="/sources#6" aria-label="Source 6">6</a>, with a new dividend-policy licence condition coming into force that year.
  </p>

  <h2>Lawful is not the same as fair</h2>

  <p>
    The rise is lawful. Ofwat approved it. The CMA heard the appeal. A lawful outcome is not automatically a fair one, and fairness is not a question for Ofwat or the CMA. It is a question for Parliament.
  </p>

  <p>
    An individual complaint about your bill goes to Southern Water. It might get you a breakdown, a social tariff, or a meter test. It will not change the rates. The structural question, about who should pay for investment that was not funded when it should have been, goes to your MP.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="btn primary" href="/complain">Draft a complaint to Southern Water</a>
    <a class="btn ghost" href="/write-to-mp">Write to your MP</a>
  </div>

  <div class="flag">
    <strong>This site is not a campaign and is not party affiliated.</strong> It was built by a local who doesn't think this is fair. It does not offer legal advice.
  </div>
</Base>
